                        <interp inst="t18800628-name-299" type="given" value="HARRY"></interp>HARRY WEBB</persName>
                  </hi>. I am one of the firm of Phillips and Webb, oil merchants—on 5th November I sold the defendants, I think it was 5 tons of linseed oil, value about 150<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., on the understanding that they were to be paid for in 14 days—they were delivered immediately after the date of the sale—I pressed for payment, but could not get it, and took proceedings—we have never received anything—we had had prior transactions with the defendants, for which they paid—we had agreed to give them credit to the amount of 1,000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—we commenced business with them in April, 1879—a bill of sale for between 400<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and 500<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. which was due in December was dishonoured.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> We took the bill up ourselves—we knew that it would not be met, and we arranged with the prisoners to take it up—we sold them about 1,500<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of goods, besides this bill and the parcel in November, inclusive of the amounts for which we have had to sue—it is most unusual in that business to get money on stock to carry it on—they told me that they were in difficulties and could not sell their stock, and I said if they were perfectly honest in their intentions I should be glad to advance money on the stock—that was the day before the bill fell due—Bultitude came to me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> The entire sum due to us now is 555<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
